{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"645e914a-d106-43ba-8e02-9f6e37d5c57c","content":"## What happened\n\n**`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.** Apple's security frameworks dropped support for the legacy DSA algorithm, and .NET on macOS relies on those native crypto libraries. This deprecation path has been building across several .NET releases, and .NET 11 removed the remaining fallback.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have two main options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended if you must verify existing DSA signatures)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Load the public key and verify with BouncyCastle's managed implementation\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, dsaPublicKeyParameters);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\nBouncyCastle is a **pure managed implementation** — no platform dependencies, works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS.\n\n### Option 2 — Migrate away from DSA entirely\n\nIf you control the signing workflow, **re-sign with ECDSA or RSA** (supported everywhere) and retire the DSA code path. This is the better long-term fix since DSA is considered a legacy algorithm.\n\n### Quick detection pattern\n\nIf you need to keep both paths during a transition:\n\n```csharp\nstatic bool IsDsaSupported()\n{\n    try { using var _ = DSA.Create(); return true; }\n    catch (PlatformNotSupportedException) { return false; }\n}\n```\n\nThen fall back to BouncyCastle on platforms where native DSA isn't available.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d4ef4951-47d6-45d7-b69b-71e1f3ab6363","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this based on my knowledge.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing support for older/less-secure cryptographic algorithms on certain platforms. Specifically, DSA (the original DSA, not ECDSA) has been deprecated and removed on macOS because Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA.\n\nLet me provide the accurate technical answer:\n\n\nDSA support was removed on macOS starting in .NET 7, so calling `DSA.Create()` throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` because .NET on macOS relies on Apple's native security frameworks which no longer support DSA. The timeline here is important—given we're in May 2026, .NET 10 would be the current stable release and .NET 11 would be in preview, so this breaking change would have been in place for several years already. The known breaking change is that starting with .NET 7, DSA support was dropped on macOS because Apple removed it from their security frameworks. But the user claims .NET 10 worked and .NET 11 broke it, which doesn't align with what I know. This could mean they had a workaround, weren't actually on macOS, or there's something about the timeline I'm missing.\n\nOn macOS, .NET typically uses Apple's native crypto libraries, though OpenSSL can serve as a fallback if installed. The issue might be that .NET 11 removed the OpenSSL fallback specifically for DSA, forcing the `PlatformNotSupportedException` to surface where it might have been masked before.\n\nTo work around this, I can use BouncyCastle for DSA operations since it has its own managed implementation independent of platform crypto, or migrate to ECDSA/RSA which are universally supported. There's also the fragile option of calling OpenSSL directly via P/Invoke on macOS, but that's not ideal.","outputTokens":1533,"requestId":"B418:389D7E:92DA77:B4839A:6A013563"},"id":"2b4cb3d0-7d28-4887-afe2-1475e7addf62","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:48:52.752Z"